{"/service/ndnp/iahi/batch_iahi_machamp_ver01/data/sn87058308/00340584120/1908062501/1038.xml":{"full_text":"XV?:t,5-tC\nA 'v\n4\nTHE OSKALOOSA HERALD.\n\nPablUhed Weakly oti \u00bbfcwriday* at\nOek&loosR. Mahaska County, lowa.\nMKALOOSA HERAL* COMPANY\nPublisher*.\nJtntered at the postofflce at Oska\nfoott, lowa, as second-class matter.\n\u2022ibicrlption. Two Dollar* PfJ Tear,\nPayable in Advance. t\nOFFICIAL COUNTY PAPER.\n<s^illpl>\n\u2014Talk about primary incongruities!\nIf three conventions in one duy aren't\nf the limit!\nk \u2014As the college man might say:\n\"Hoo Kali. Hoo Rah; Hurrah by Hen;\nTaft and Sherman are the men!\u201d\n\u2014\"Dolliver is satisfied in the sen\nate and the iieople are satisfied to\nhave him there,\"says the Ames Times.\n\u2014At Cincinnati: mil\u2014\" Jim. were\nIT, and it's up to usenses to make\ngood.\u201d \"That's right, Bill, and we'uns\nwill, by gum!\u201d\nI \u2014\"No one,\" it is remarked, \u2018ever\nheard of a farmer being out of work.\"\n4 The trouble that farmers contend with\nis that they are often out of workers.\n\u2014\"Curiosity is not confined to worn\nen,\" observes the Keokuk Gnte-City.\n\u201cThe auditor of lowa county was so\nanxious to ascertain the result of the\nprimary that he opened the poll books\nH and counted the votes. Some rlpirp\nA this may invalidate the whole votf in\niS that county.\u201d\n\u2014The only two people in lowa not\nj- satisfied with the Chicago ticket and\nplatform, are the editors of the Des\nMoines Register and Leader and the\nMarshalltown Times-Uepublic.in. A\n1 dose of wliat mother used to give\nwhen the boys had eaten too many\nv cherries might relieve the distress.\n\u2014Dr. Wilson S. Lewis, of Sioux City,\nf who was recently elected Bisnop hy\nthe Methodist General Conference.\nand who will retire ns tbc head til\nMorningside college next November,\nX has announced to the board of trustees\nthat at his departure he wjll present\nto the college his SIO,O!Kt home, whicn\nis fixated within .two .squares of the\ncajnpus.\n\u2014After a-heated discussion on the\nproposition of changing i-e nomenela\n.44lre-wf-Jhe. ehuroh, which lasted for\nthree hours, the Cbnrch of the Breth\nren is the new name adopted at the\nDunhariti* conference held in lies\nMoines. The Christian Brethren and\nDunkard Brethren were the other\nnames brought before the conference\nin the report of the committee. The\nold official name has been the German\nBaptist Brethren. The arguments\nagainst the name \"Dunker\" were the\nmost heated. The term has always\nbeen applied more as a nickname, and\nhas never been officially recognized.\nNATIONAL CREDIT.\nIn his speech as temporary chair\nman of the republican national con\nvention Senator Burrows stated \u2014at\nduring the present administration the\npublic debt has decreased SIuLO\u00bbU,-\n000 and the annual interest charge\nhas been reduced from $00,000,000 to\n$21,000,000. The last item is the most\nimportant, as it is a yearly saving.\nand in less than a quarter of a cen\ntury would be more than equivalent\nto the cost of the Panama canal. A\nsaving in interest on this scale is a\ngn at national achievement. Only the\nbest credit in the world could bring\nalxjut such a reduction. During the\ncivil war the government paid interest\nat the rate of over 7 per cent. It bor\nrows money now for 2 per cent, or\nless when the premium obtained is\nconsidered.\nC. N. Marvin in the Shenandoah\nSentiue!~Po3t: But few of you knew\nmy mother. You would not be inter\nested in the story of her simple life,\nnor in the manner of her death. So\nfar as you might give it a thought it\nwould lie simply in the tact that i had\nbeen bereaved. But it seems to me\nthat I owe this duty to her memory\nto say to you. to whom I speak from\nweek to week, as from heart to ueart,\nthat she was a good woman, the best\nfriend I ever had. Man finds no other\nfriend in life so true as that of moth\ner. A child may forget the parent, the\nwife may turn against the husband if\nhe prove unfaithful, even a father may\nfail in his duty to his child, but it is\nrare indeed mat a mother\u2019s love ever\nchanges or her devotion falters. No\nmatter how worthless or unworthy\nher sou may prove ui lie. she loves\nhim still, and her heart finds lnlinite\nexcuses for his faults. When he falls\nshort of her desire# or expectations\nshe blames herself, believing that in\nsome manner she had failed to tram\nhim aright. Every grief, every sor\nrow and ever)' disapimintment of his\nlife finds instant response in her heart.\nBlows aimed at him pierce her. Chief\namong the treasures my mother left\nwere old letters and clippings from\nmy newspaper, bits of sentiment mat\nI had long since forgotten. On me\nday when the battle of the ballots\nwaged fiercely hero in Shenandoah her\nfour sons, all the children she ever\nhud. laid her away in a country grave\nyard ill Ohio. The day was one of\nrarest beauty, whore, sunshine ami\nyj}\nHIS MOTHER.\npi WBRSa\nbalmy air and fragrant flowers com\nbined to make the scene one of hal\nlowed memory while life shall last.\nAROUND THF. CIRCUIT.\nHussey Press: If the C., H. Q.\nwould install a motor and single car\nservice between Albia and Oskaloosa\nto make four or five trips each way\neach -day. Uie passenger traffic en\nroute would be increased five tithes yi\nless than three months. The Oska-\nJoo*a- branch brought it people to\nTracy Monday morning, took 40 peo\nple back to Oskaloosa at 11 o'clock,\nthen brought about 30 in the even\ning and took another bunch back. We\nasked a \u201dQ\" man what he thought\nof our plan to install this interurban\nservice and he replied emphatically\nthat it was just the thing to do. He\nindorsed our idea of the increased\ntraffic and said' it would solve the in\nterurban problem between Oskaloosa\nand Albia. It woulu benefit both cit\nies and help the towns between.\nHurlington Hawk-Eye: Oskaloosa\nheld a special election a few days ago\nand voted in favor of enlarging and re\nmodeliug a school house. The sum\nto be expended was not so very great,\nonly $7,000, but the vote is what\nmakes it interesting. Oskaloosans\nseem to be able to get together U|ion\nany project that is for the real bene\nfit of Oskaloosa. Of the total vote of\n367>. but 4S were opposed to the ex\npenditure of the money for the need\ned improvements. There have been\nother lowa towns where new sejtool\nhouses were urgently needed and\nwhere the propositions were voted\ndown repeatedly. Hut after nil spch\ncases are rare in lowa, and the Oakn\nloosa way is really the lowa way.\nR R\nAlbia Republican: Talk aboyt a\nbusy man: James (5. Patterson.-of! Os\nkaloosa, and an uncle of W. J. tyend\nof this city, is that man. He 'was\nmarried last week to Miss Maude Mc-\nClure. of Oskaloosa, anjj then besides\nhe is a candidate for county attorney\nof Mahaska county. Mr. Head was\nover to the wedding and he says the\nuncle is the busiest man in Proud\nMahaska. He was busy pursuing the\ngoddess of Hove for a time and now\nIt is the political favor which he must\npursue. j\n\u2014The army of fellows who went to\nschool with Taft will now increase\nrapidly.\n\u2014Sunday was the longest day in\nthe year. We are again oyer the hill\ntoward winter.\n-.\u2014Wendef tiow much of,-that $300,-\n000,000 the Burlington will spend on\na new depot in Oskaloosa'.\u2019\n\u2014it should be kept in mind flint\nMe. Lumpers, who Is finding so imich\nfault with the republican platform, is\na democrat-\n\u2014lf local fields show knee-high corn\nby the Fourth of July this season,\nthere must be some humping done on\nthe part of Mr. Corn.\n\u2014Bryan says the republican party\nis in full retreat. But Bryan said\nthat same thing twice before when an\nOhio man beat him out. \"Buckeyes\"\nare sour grapes for Bryan.\n\u2014When the news of Taft's nomina\ntion reached the White House. Presi\ndent Roosevelt was out on the lawn.\nSecretary Loeb shouted the result to\nhim out of the wipdow. \"Bully!\"was\nthe President's only reply. But that\n.was enough.\n\u2014lt Is estimated that the delegates\nand visitors to the republican national\nconvention spent over a million dol\nlars in Chicago hotels, stores and\nplaces of amusement. Chicago has\ngood reason to work for a continu\nante of republican prosperity.\n\u2014The eloquence of this little sliver\nof one of the planks of the republican\nplatform was never surpassed in\nAmerican literature; \"In principle, the\ndifference between democracy and re\npublicanism is that one Htands for vacil\nlation and timidity in government, the\nother for strength and purpose; one\nstands for obstruction, the other for\nconstruction; one promises, the other\nperforms; one finds fault, the other\nfind# work.\"\nTHE BUSINESS OUTLOOK.\nHenry Clews in his weekly review\nof trade says: Now that the Chicago\nconvention is over, and that Mr.\nTaft has secured the nomination, the\npolitical outlook has been much clari\nfied. Unless unforeseen events inter\nfere, Mr. Taft will he our next presi\ndent. His high character, ability and\nlong experience in public affair* af\nford promise of a satisfactory and\nsuccessful administration. The Koosc\nvelt policies will be continued, but in\na more deliberate and less disturbing\nfashion. On the Stock Ex\nchange we may look for a comparative\nly quiet summer. The storm is over\nand the danger signals are down. Ab\nsenteeism will also soon he a factor\nin the market. Meanwhile no pro\nnounced setbacks are probable; and\nprices will no doubt respond readily\nto favorable developments. Easy\nmoney is a certainty for months.\nBank reserves are piling tip both at\nhome and abroad.\nThe future, therefore now chiefly\ndepends upon the crops. As is al\nready known these are very promis\ning; the larger acreage and the gen\nerally high condition of grain, cotton,\nhay. fruits and vegetables all assur\ning the fnnnem of a profitable year.\n-Uine. however, is usually the period o!\nhighest condition for many of the\ncrops; July and August are frequently\nmonths of deterionation, and Septem\nber always brings the danger of frost\nto corn and cotton, two of our princi\npal crops. To tnls extent, then, the\nfuture is uncertain; yet, allowing for\nthe average loss in condition during\nthe past ten years, we should still\nhave crops much above the average,\nfor which profitable prices will v t)e<\nhad. and of which Europe win Jalfe\nall we can spare. ei|\nTake advantage of the Stock\nReducing Sale at J. R. McGreg\nor\u2019s.\nMarlon Hoover has been picking\ncherries for J. A. Reynolds.\nMr. and Mrs. H. D. Lane visited at\nthe Milton Mney home Sunday after\nnoon\nMr. and Mrs. J. G. Reynolds, of\nLacey, visited with their son one day\nthis week.\nOpal Pettitt visited at the home of\nMary and Lucille Reynolds Friday\nafternoon.\nMr. and Mrs. Ed Butler returned to\ntheir home in Burlington and Miss\nMabel Butler accompanied them for\na short visit.\nMr. and: Mrs. X u;S. [Reynolds re\nturned fdom Colfax. Saturday. Mrs.\nRey/oldsi rem.Vned at lioum, but Mr.\nReynolds returned Holiday morning\nfor' another week's (treatment.\nJ. B. chitijen\u2019fe' 'feodse, on hist farm,\nwas totally destroy erf by tire Sunday\nmorning. The house was occupied\nliy Harry Hicks and family, wno saved\nmost of t'lieir\u2019 household furniture.\nElmer Waters, of the local post of\nflee force, who is serving as substi\ntute on one of the rural delivery\nroutes, had a runaway Saturday that\nsmashed up his rig and caused some\nlittle damage. Pete had driven t 6 ihe\nside of a mail box and alighted from\nthe rig. He threw the reins over his\narm while attending to the distribu\ntion of mail, the horse scared ami\nstarted to run. Pete was jerked oh\nhis feet and pulled into the rig. lie\nwas compelled to release his hold on\nthe lines or have his arm drawn into\nthe wheel of the conveyance. Waters\nwas not hurt to any extent.\nBroken Arm Causes Death.\nWilliam Rynearson, brother ot\nTheodore Rynearson, of Delta, died\nJune 9. He was working at carpen\ntering at Tipton, when he fell and\nbroke his avm; blood poison set ,ii)\nwith the above result.\nThat\u2019s What Our\n$9.75\nSuit Sale\nis making.\nOf course,' there\u2019s good\nSi )If\npicking now.i Just how\nlong there wilt b\u2019e, how\never,' we are not pre-\npared to say, more than\nif they keep on picking\nlike they did Saturday\nand Monday, it will soon\nbe a case of \u201cpicked.\u201d\nA great many people are\nlooking forward to the\n4th, and taking advant\nage of the sale early.\nAre you coming to Os\nkaloosa on the 4th? It\u2019s\ngoing to be the biggest\ncelebration ever pulled\noff. You are cordially\ninvited to make our store\nyour headquarters ahd j\nresting place. 1/\nTHE\nHUB\nCLOTHIERS\nTrunks Bags Valises\nP. R.\u2014Our store will be closed\nMONDAY, JULY 6 h, to give the\nclerks s holiday.\nTHE OSKAXOOSA lIERALH. TfTTTJSDAT, JUNE 25 1908\nLINCOLN.\nHorse Ran Away.\nBig'\nHit!\nximfr v\nLow Prices on Furniture!\nAt McCurdy\u2019s.\nOur Special Low Price Sale tojreduce stock, preparatory to Fall purchases,\nwill save you dollars. Buy now and get the benellt ol Our Immense Slock to\nselect Irom. Everything Reduced. Nothing Held Back. Come In and See.\nA fine quarter-sawed\noak cabinet, former\nprice 7.5 D, special\nprice 5.95\nMahogany finished\ncabinet, polished 7.G5\nNice Birch Mahog\nany cabinet with french\nplate mirror 9.85\n\nSplit,! Mahogany Cabinet, was specfil\nprice\nRecord Cabinet in. golden oak\nholds 100 records for; phonograph IB.SO\nDisc Cabinet in golden oak, holds\nOf, discs ..'V. J 9.00\n\u2022i' I r. u\nRattan Go-Carts\nA fine rattan cart like\nena m ele d en\nMcCurdy\u2019s for Good Goods at Right Prices\nJ. B. McCurdy Co.\nNortH of Court House\nREV. S. R. ZENOT\nMADE PRESIDENT\nOSKALOOSA MAN HONORED\nCHRISTIAN CHURCHES.\nSTATE MEETING IN SESSION.\nSome Accomplishments And Needs ot\nThe Denomination Set Forth\nin Annual Reports and\nDiscussions.\nDos Moines June 23.\u2014The Rev. S.\n11. Zendt, of Oskaloosa, was elected\npresident of the lowa Christian con\nvention at the convention session last\nnight. Other members of the direc\ntory bonrd are: .J. D. Corbett, vice\npresident; J. J. Grove,* recording sec\nretary, and J. M. Lucas, treasurer. 11.\n3. Denny, of Dea Molne\u00df, was elected\ncorresponding secretary for the elev\nenth time.\n.Tb* convention officers for next\nyrtnr or those who will have charge of\nthe convention sessions are: Arthu*\nLong, J. H. Hallow, C. H. Morris 3. B.\nRoss and E. E. Mack.\nThe standing committee for tne year\nwill be: .1. U. Corbi* D. R. Dungnn.\nW. T. Fisher, E.\u201d E. Mack, Irving\nBrown, D. 3. Thompson, E. W. Par\ndell and Lew C. Harris.\nThe Rev. W. T. Fisner, of Clarindu,\ngave the convention address last even\ning. He emphasized tho Importance\nof lowa missions. lowa, lie said, was\nan agricultural state of first rank with\n50,025 square mfles ajmt 2,2(1,1inn ot\nth\u00ab best people.' *ibwti has Indus\ntriads, law \u00fcbiding and peace loving\nHP?\nMusic\nCabinets\nGo-Cart like\ncut $1.45.\nFlat folding cart, veneer seat\nand back, G steel frame and\nwheels .enameled green, hard\nmaple frame, regular price 2.25\nnow 1 .45\npeople devotudl-.lto-eldeals of citizen\nship,\u2019'.said theiffiev.-Mr; iFlsher. \"Yet\nthere -aiV>i fouiifieen counties that are\nwithout ithe nlmrch we- lOvb in them.\nThis m-cniis liba4 ihfirn ifc a great re\nsponsibility. aih.i\n\u201cThese' oifpdftunitioS' ,t demand <jon\nsiderable preparation. 'We need men\nti:.C money.\u2019 The New York L\u2014ntral\nplaces men in school and pays them\nwages while they are there that they\nmay be fitted for the work later on.\nThis is what the church should do.\nThere are hundreds of churches in\nlowa that are in need of trained min-\nI Isters and these congregations are\ngoing to pieces because we have not\nthe men.\"\nConvention Notes.\nThe Christian church in lowa last\nyear raised $11,478.12 for the church\nI work In the state.\nAs a result of the centennial free will\noffering taken Sunday at the maks\nmcetlng $247.70 was received for tne\nevangelistic work in the state. 04\nthis amount $201.20 was received in\ncash and $10.50 in pledges.\n1 The afternoon session yesterday\nwas given over to the ministerial in\nstitute with short uddressos from min-\nBmu I--\nr\u2014\nHealth\u2014\nEconomy,^\u2014\n/Galumeti\nL Baking J\nPowder J\nV fc-Best by Test 'T\nJ\nAs an example of our\ncut prices, here are a\nfew sample prices on\nChina Closets\nNice Quartered Oak\nChina Closet, Bent\nClass Ends, Double\ngrooved shelves, neat,\nhandsome, and well\nmade, Special-\nPrice sl4-95\n$20.00 China Closets, $16.00\n$22.50 China Closets, SIB.OO\n$25.00 China Closets, $20.00\n$30.00 China Closets, $24.00\n$40.00 China Closets, $32.00\n$50.00 China Closets, $40.00\nThis Refrigerator\nis no experiment. We have sold it\nten years. It\u2019s an ICE SAVER, and\nthat means money in your pocket,\nboth when you buy it and when\nyou use it. 1-5 OFF.\ninters in the s'ate oil the general topic\nof church work. These talks were\nmade by B. F. Shoemaker, B. VV. Pettit\nA. B. Cornell, C. H. Strawn and J. J.\nGrove.\nAa an exhibit of the work done oy\nthe lowa Christian convention lor the\npast year, the report of the treasurer\nshows that $11,578.19 has been receiv\ned for the general fund. For the per\nmanent fund there was $2,000 and the\namount of cash raised in the tieiu\nwork, $33,037.06.\nThe Rev. Burris A. Jenkins, of Kan\nsas City, Mo., one of the ablest men\nin the Church of Christ, will give the\naddress this evening at the lowa Chris\ntian convention. He was formerly\npresident of the Lexington, I<y., col\nlege. His subject will be: \"The Plea\nof the Disciples of Cfcrist the Ultimate\nof Protestantism.\"\nOf all toe young men whom he had\nsent Into the ministry. Dr. 1). It. Dun\ngan, head of the Drake Bible School,\ncertified yesterday afternoon In ills\naddress that not one had been tile son\nof a rich man. The men had come\nfrom the farm, were rugged and with\na definite pur|\u00ab>se in life. \u201cWith the\nstrong rural blood in their veins.'\nsaid Dr. Dungan, \"these men ere the\nbest of their kind in the world.\nIn his report to the convention B. S.\nDenny, corresponding secretary gave\na history of a busy year. He deliver\ned 163 sermons and addresses. He\nvisited 47 churches, attended 7 dis\ntrlct conferences, 5 district and 12\ncounty conventions. And along with\nall this work In the state ho gave a\npaper before the national secretaries'\nmeeting at Norfolk and delivered an\naddress at the Indiana state .ponv'n\ntlon.\nThe general benevolent departments\nof the church were reviewed yeoterday\nmorning, Xhv work.of the church exi\ntension was given by G. W. Mucwly,\nWW\nPS?\nJ. A\u2019* 1\nChina\nNATIONAL\nREFRIGERATORS.\nAll Sample Refrig\nerators of tHis cel\nebrated National\nBrand. The Best\nREFRIGERATOR\nmade, at a snap.\nOskaloosa, lowa\nof Kansas City, Mo., the benevolent\nassociation, G. H. Mooreharder; for\neign missionary work, A. M. McClain,\nof Cincinnati; centennial secretary\nwork, W. R. Warren; American mis\nsionary society, W. T. Moore, and min\nisterial relief, G. B. Van Ardall, of\nCedar Rapids.\nIT\u2019S NOT\nTOO LATE!\nHalf of 1908 is almost\ngone. Where is the\nmoney you earned\nBince New Year\u2019s. If\nyou did not start the\njbar right by opening\na Havings Account,\ncome to THIS BANK\nnow, open an accouuc,\nand nave your money\nduring the second half\nof the year.\nWe aid and\noar depositors.\nMahaska County\nState Bank\nCapital, Murplua\nand Profits\n$175,000.00\nEm\nClosets\ni","height":"25072","width":"19972"}}
